>”Welcome home.”
>Ah, her voice.
>So calm, so reassuring.
>The cave she dwelled in was darker than anything you’d ever known.
>But it was fine.
>She was your friend who you loved to help.
>Very carefully you pulled the wheel barrow further in, not letting it make a sound.
>This dank setting was a stark contrast to the wastes, but you knew how to find your way to her by now.
>And before long there she was, leaning over a cauldron.
>One that bubbled, toiled, and troubled with frothing green liquid, smoke that reached the cave’s ceiling.
>”Thank you for your efforts. Just leave your findings here and make yourself comfortable.”
>Ethereal, soft. Like she wasn’t really here.
>Her voice was similar to the rest of your friend’s body.
>Or lack thereof.
>That is, she was a towering pillar of green fluid, completely different from fleshy things like you.
>Her body was wrapped in several bandages and her head a horned skull with fierce blue embers for eyes.
>You supposed that anyone would find your friend’s appearance horrifying.
>But in these parts, you didn’t have time to be concerned with such things.
>Having this cave to lounge around in was all you needed.
>And so you did as your friend asked, leaving the wheel barrow to rest at her side.
>One by one each piece of that poor fellow’s body was lifted into the air, suspended by faint trails of green magic.
>One by one they were dropped into the cauldron, his head hissing one last complaint before disappearing.

>You just found her abilities so fascinating.
>Like how she now churned and churned an enormous ladle within, swirling fluid and organs into an unrecognizable blur.
>Before you knew it, she’d finished.
>Nothing happened.
>For a moment.
>Then a hand reached out of the cauldron.
>A foot found purchase on the edge.
